A MAN who was accused of robbery and attempted murder after the robbery of G4S security guards has been found guilty and sentenced. Mfundo Mpondombi (31) was handed a 23-year sentence by the Bethal Regional Court on Friday, 20 March. He had pleaded not guilty. According to Mpumalanga Hawks spokeswoman Captain Dineo Sekgotodi, the sentence followed an incident which took place on 12 October 2018 where G4S security guards were robbed while collecting money from a shop in Bethal, Mpumalanga. “It is alleged that on the day in question the crew went to the shop to collect money. After collection a crew member came out with the trolley bag when he was accosted by the suspect, who shot and wounded him, grabbed the trolley bag and ran away with it. “The police and security gave chase and managed to arrest the first suspect. The second suspect who shot the crew member ran away. The stolen money was recovered. “On 23 November 2018, information was received about the whereabouts of the suspect and an operation was conducted by Secunda Serious Organised Crime Investigation and Secunda Crime Intelligence. “The address was visited at Emzinoni, Bethal, where the suspect was arrested. He was detained until his case was finalised and he was sentenced.” Accused number one Sandile Thabethe (29) pleaded guilty and was sentenced to 10 years’ direct imprisonment by the same court on 6 October 2020. “Mpondombi was sentenced to 15 years’ imprisonment for armed robbery and eight years for attempted murder. The sentences will run concurrently,” said Sekgotodi.